[2026-03-18T18:20:18.937Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PPygDmQhzyvtBuxX5qEjHF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Scan ID is `fd9ffafc-8fa7-4268-9862-1be3eb47cf77`. Now let me submit the ideas.\n\nMy analysis reveals these key gaps in the OAuth & Token Management context:\n\n1. **No token persistence across restarts** - Tokens live only in memory. Vault, Auth0, and every production OAuth implementation persists tokens.\n\n2. **No proactive token health monitoring** - Refresh only happens reactively when `getValidAccessToken()` is called. Best-in-class systems (Auth0, Okta) proactively monitor and refresh tokens before they're needed.\n\n\n3. **Hardcoded single-provider OAuth** - Only Anthropic is supported via hardcoded constants, whereas modern API gateways like Kong and Auth0 handle multiple OAuth providers seamlessly.\n\n4. **No retry/backoff on refresh failure** - A single failed refresh returns null and authentication is lost, unlike production systems such as Stripe that implement exponential backoff with circuit breakers.\n\n5. **Decrypted token cache never expires** - The `decryptedCache` in tokenManager has no TTL, so plaintext tokens persist indefinitely in memory instead of using lease-based TTLs like Vault does.\n\nLet me submit these 5 ideas.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":341,"cache_read_input_tokens":49415,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":341},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1c0f81e8-c3c1-45e4-9bc5-d19d70c61f73","uuid":"cace861b-7592-4a6d-bf5a-e7af9d3dab37"}
